**3.4.2 Source Data:**   
Our data source comes from a kaggle dataset created by the user Brupley with the original file being named dancing\_with\_the\_stars\_dataset.xlsx. The original file had just one sheet that included several columns regarding celebrity, partner, season, scores and placement information. We exported, edited and updated the original data file to an excel file titled New\_dwts.xlsx, which contained more detailed data on every season of the TV show *Dancing with the Stars*. The file includes four sheets: 1\) celeb\_info sheet (includes Brupley’s original data and contains basic information on each celebrity who has competed) 2\) judge\_scores (contains the judges scores for each celeb each week from Brupley’s original file) 3\) judges (this sheet was created completely by ourselves and contains the name of the judges for each season and which order they scored with judge1\_score being the leftmost judge and judge2\_score being the right most judge) 4\) hosts (this sheet was created completely by ourselves and contains the names of the hosts and the season they hosted) 5\) dance\_styles (this sheet was created completely by ourselves and used the data from wikipedia to find the dances performed each week for each celeb per season) and lastly 6\) season\_info (this sheet was also created completely by ourselves and used the data from wikipedia to find the season’s premiere date, finale date, premiere views, finale views, and the number of episodes aired). Also, we added the most recent season 33 data to our modified excel file as it was not  included in Brupley’s original file. We selected this dataset because we thought that it was messy enough to require major transformations to meet the project's requirements for real-world, structured, and normalized data and had complex many-to-many relationships (e.g., celebrities performing multiple dances across multiple seasons), that gave us the opportunity to create our own relational design. We also bonded over our interest in *Dancing with the Stars* as we both ended up going on the Dancing with the Stars Tour in Charlotte with our siblings. We were also interested in learning more about how the show works and learning more about trends of the show. The final dataset we used met the project requirements due to its large size, complexity, inaccuracies and inefficiencies which made the data cleaning and transformation process challenging.

**3.4.3 Database Design:**   
We carefully separated season-specific attributes from celebrity-specific data, avoided redundancy, and removed any transitive dependencies. Below is an explanation of our normalization process and structure to ensure our data is in 3rd Normal Form:

1. Table 1: Celebrity  
   1. This table stores general information about each celebrity, such as name, industry, homestate, and home country. It contains one row per unique celebrity, even if the celebrity appears in multiple seasons. We also created a primary key called celebrity\_id. This table prevents redundancy and isolates non-season-specific data.   
2. Table 2: Season  
   1. This table stores general information about each season. It contains each season number and ensures each season is unique. We also created a primary key called season\_id to avoid transitive dependencies. This table is linked to the celebrity season table through a foreign key called season\_id.  
3. Table 3: Pros  
   1. This table uniquely identifies every ballroom professional that has ever competed on DWTS. We also created a primary key called pro\_id to avoid transitive dependencies. This table is important to include for 3NF because most of the ballroom partners competed with different celebrities across many seasons (and this isolates non-season-specific dance partner data).   
4. Table 4: Celebrity Season  
   1. This table connects celebrities to a specific season(s) they participated in. It also contains season-specific details like the celebrity’s ballroom partner, placement, and result (for that specific season). This design ensures that returning celebrities have distinct season entries. We created a primary key called celebrity\_season\_id to uniquely identify the celebrity the season they competed in, and the season’s specific information for that celebrity. This primary key was dependent on the celebrity\_id, season\_id and pro\_id foreign keys. The unique constraint on celebrity\_id and season\_id ensures that each celebrity can only appear once per season.  
5. Table 5: Judges  
   1. This table contains judge names and assigns each judge a unique ID, since judges changed throughout the show across seasons, and some seasons had 4 total judges. We included a primary key called judge\_id to avoid transitive dependencies and link to other tables.   
6. Table 6: Score  
   1. This table stores weekly scores for each celebrity-season pair. Since the original data set gives only one averaged score per week per judge (even if multiple dances are performed and multiple scores were given), we stored only one score per celebrity per week. We enforce one row per celebrity per week using a unique constraint. We created a primary key called score\_id to uniquely identify the celeb, season (we referenced the foreign key celerity\_season\_id to do this), and that week’s set of judges scores. The unique constraint on celebrity\_season\_id and week ensures that each celebrity’s performance in a specific season can only have one score entry per week (to comply with Brupleys original file).  
7. Table 7: Judges Scores  
   1. This table connects contestants and judges to their scores each week for a specific season. It stores the celebrity based on their celebrity\_season\_id, the judge\_id primary key from the judges table, the score\_id from the score table, and the score given. This table normalizes the data for seasons when there were 4 judges instead of just 3, and each celebrity and their associated judge score will be given a unique primary key dependent on the celebrity\_season\_id, judge\_id and score\_id foreign keys.   
8. Table 8: Dance Styles  
   1. This table acts as a reference table that lists all unique dance styles. It avoids repetition of dance names and ensures standardized entries. We created a primary key called dance\_id to uniquely identify each dance style.  
9. Table 9: Dances Performed  
   1. This table logs each dance style a celebrity performs in a given week and season. This table is separate from the score table to avoid violating 3NF, as a celebrity can perform multiple dances in one week (yet will receive only one score a week). We created a primary key called performance\_dance\_id where each row represents one dance performed by a celeb during a specific week. We reference the foreign key celebrity\_season\_id to identify the specific season a particular celeb competed in and dance\_id to identify the specific dance done.  
10. Table 10: Hosts  
    1. This table contains the host names and assigns each host a unique ID, since the hosts changed throughout the show across seasons (one row per host). We included a primary key called host\_id to avoid transitive dependencies and link to other tables.  
11. Table 11: Host Seasons  
    1. This table connects hosts to the specific season they hosted. This design ensures that returning hosts have distinct season entries. Multiple hosts can appear in a season and each host can appear in multiple seasons. This table allows seasons to have more than one host and allows hosts to appear in more than one season. We created a primary key called host\_season\_id to uniquely identify the host and the season they hosted. This primary key was dependent on thehost\_id and season\_id foreign keys. The unique constraint on season\_id and host\_id ensures a specific host can only be assigned once per season.  
12. View: Total Scores  
    1. Since including the total\_scores in the scores table violates 3rd normal form as it is transitively dependent on judge1\_score, judge2\_score, judge3\_score, and judge4\_score we decided to create a view that allows us to see the total score for a celebrity each week for a given season. This view calculates the total judge score per celebrity per week per season, regardless of whether there were 3 or 4 judges that season. This view aggregates data across the judges\_score, score, celebrity\_season, celebrity, season and pros table. It allows for streamlined analysis without altering main tables.  
13. Procedure: Get Dance Celebrity History  
    1. This stored procedure prints information about each dance a celebrity competed. It's useful for generating quick and easy summaries without manually querying multiple tables.  
    2. Parameters: celeb\_name (the name of the celebrity who competed in the show)  
    3. Returns: This function returns all the dances performed by a celebrity per week and for each season they competed in.  
14. Function: Pro season  
    1. We created a function called pro\_seasons This function allows the user to input the name of a professional dancer (ballroom\_partner) who competed on the show and the number of seasons. This function is useful for quickly retrieving information about when different professionals competed (since most of them competed in multiple seasons of the show).   
    2. Parameters: ballroom\_partner (the name of a professional dancer who competed on the show) and season\_data (a season number 1 \- 33).  
    3. Returns: This function returns data if that ballroom partner competed during a season, their placement, and their celebrity partner.

**3.4.4 Analysis and Reflection Questions:** 

We faced several challenges in transforming the DWTS Excel data into a normalized schema. There were many caveats and nuances to the data that definitely made creating the database more challenging than we initially thought. We also found that there isn’t much publicly available data on Dancing with the Stars. In the original excel file created by Bruperly, we found that many columns were encoded with week-specific values (e.g., week1\_judge1\_score, week1\_judge2\_score, week1\_judge3\_score etc.-- all the way through week 12), requiring iterative transformations and reformatting for weekly performance tracking. When loading the scores data, we ended up renaming the columns to just be judge1\_score, judge2\_score, judge3\_score and judge4\_score which required pivoting the data. Additionally, since some weeks/seasons included a fourth main judge (guest judge scores were not included in this data), we had to figure out how to incorporate this score while maintaining 3rd Normal Form. We resolved this issue by creating Judges Scores and Judge ID tables where we could connect judge scores to a particular judge using a primary key (and avoid an additional column for judge 4 with a bunch of Null values since most weeks only had 3 judges). We also pivoted the week by creating a new week column. After meeting with Professor Benbow we kept our original scores table but excluded total scores (as total scores was transitively dependent on judge 1-4 scores) and then also created the judges score table as stated above that provides the specific score given by each judge per week. We also had to ensure we accurately connected each celebrity to the right season specific information (like the correct ballroom partner, placement etc.) which became more difficult because of the returning all-star celebrities from season 15\. Something difficult throughout the whole process was navigating transitive dependencies, due to the complexity of the data set. For example, initially the celebrity table started out not referencing the foreign key celebrity\_id and instead was dependent on the celebrity name column included in the table which violated 3rd normal form. Additionally, we had to filter out invalid score rows (with all zero or null values) using a DELETE statement after initial loading, as some contestants were eliminated early, and lacked complete score data yet. Therefore to reduce redundancy, we wanted to drop all the rows where all the judge’s scores were null (i.e. indicating that the celebrity did not make it to that week, withdrew from the competition and or dropped out). In the score table, we still kept the judge4\_score even though for most of the seasons it was null and we felt like removing it would lose the show’s historical data, future seasons could still have 4 main judges, and would require significant changes to the schema. Also when creating the judges score we initially had week included but had to remove week as score was transitively dependent on week and was redundant. Therefore we had to create a score\_id in the score table that included a week table.

Additionally, we had to create a separate Partners table since most of the ballroom partners competed in multiple seasons. Like previously said, some rows had 0 or NULL scores due to celebrities being eliminated before or due to not having a 4th judge that week. This required an update/delete operation to clean the scores. For example, when testing our database we found 11 NULL values for Stacey Keibler, and we resolved the issue by correcting inconsistent naming. Originally we had the ballroom partners in the celebrity season table where we used the ballroom partner name to join on. However, we realized we needed to create a separate table to uniquely identify the ballroom professional partners and then join on a primary key (i.e. pro\_id) because the ballroom partner can be in multiple seasons and to ensure that there is not a transitive dependency on celebrity season. There were also a few seasons where the celebrity got partnered with a different professional pro then the original one they were assigned to for one week (in the show it was referred to as switch up week), but because Brupley did not include this we also did not include this. Therefore, in our database for each season the celebrity was assigned to one ballroom professional. There were also a few times where a ballroom pro got COVID, was sick or injured and thus the celebrity was assigned to a different pro for that week. Because Brupley didn’t include the rare occurrences of this happening, we also did not include this. Another caveat with the pros table is that Brupley did not include the ballroom professionals in the troupe. The DWTS troupe was introduced in season 12 and being a troupe member means they are not assigned a celebrity partner and only participate in the opening number dances. Most ballroom professionals often start out in a troupe and then work their way up to be partnered with a celebrity. Therefore, the pros listed only include only the pros who have been assigned a celebrity partner.

A big difficulty was that there were celebrities who competed in multiple seasons, like in Season 15, which was an all-star season featuring past contestants, so this required careful normalization to avoid duplications and ensure accurate season assignments. This was difficult when considering the scores each celebrity gets for each specific season they competed on. For example we had to create a unique celebrity table (to uniquely identify each celeb) and celebrity season table (to uniquely identify the scores, dances etc. received for that celeb in that season). Also, because of the limited *Dancing with the Stars* data, the dance style data was difficult to incorporate and was created in a separate excel sheet. Therefore, it had to be cleaned and joined manually over several tables when we were populating our database, which was a difficult and complex task.

Designing the schema to satisfy 3NF involved separating parts of the data across multiple tables and was a consistent problem when designing the database. For example, we initially tried to merge scores and dance styles to appear together in one table, but we realized  the need to split them to avoid repeating judge data across multiple rows. It was also important that we identified the connection between celebrities and seasons in anchoring our design as this was a consistent hardship we had to work around. One major decision was creating a separate dances\_performed table rather than combining it with score, as doing so would have violated the rules of third normal form and introduced redundancies. Balancing granularity with usability was a recurring challenge, but normalization ultimately helped us build a clean schema. Also, like previously noted, not every judge's individual score was collected each week. In weeks with more than one performance and more than one score given, average scores for each judge were used in the original dataset, so we had to account for that when creating our database and establishing relationships. This was difficult when trying to connect the dance performance table with the scores table as there were more dances than there were scores (i.e. if multiple different dance styles were performed, each dance performance for that celeb has the same score because only one score was given to the celeb each week). For example, if in week 10 the celeb does the Cha-cha and Freestyle dance performance, in our database they will receive the same score. In the future, if we were to completely create Brupley’s data from scratch we would record each individual dance performance score so that we can more accurately correlate scores with specific dance styles (i.e. does the freestyle score higher than contemporary?).

 Another caveat to the data set was that group dances, dance-offs, and the Season 1 rematch data were excluded from the original data set. Therefore, only individual performances were retained in the dances\_performed table and scores table. Also there was one season where one single dance performance was a mix of two different styles. Because of this, we ended up splitting up the two styles when reporting the dance styles the celeb did that week even though the 2 styles occurred in one performance (i.e. we decided to count the 2 styles each as their own “performance” in the dance\_performed table). Connecting dance styles with weekly performances was complex due to a lack of a common identifier between the excel sheets and the tables. Several merges with the excel file and the SQL table’s were required. Most weeks had 3 judges, but some had 4 main judges, which was another difficult challenge we had to navigate. Also, another caveat to this data is that it did not include guest judge scores. Therefore the database schema was designed to accommodate this, and week-specific adjustments were made during the creation and loading of our database. Additionally, originally we did not have a seasons column in the dance\_styles sheet, so when trying to create the dances\_performed table we kept running into issues of not having enough information to uniquely identify the celebrities leaving us with no way to connect the dance\_styles table and the scores table. Therefore, we had added the season column to the dance\_styles excel sheet so we could join the tables more precisely. 

Another crucial part of our database design was creating unique constraints on the celebrity\_season, score, and host\_season table to ensure data integrity and hopefully prevent some entry errors. In the celebrity\_season table, the unique constraint on celebrity\_id and season\_id was put to ensure that each celebrity can only appear once per season in the table. We did this because the celebrity season table represents the participation of celebrities in specific seasons. Therefore, if a celebrity was accidentally inserted multiple times in the same season (like accidentally got swapped with a different celeb, with a different pro or result etc.), this constraint would prevent any inaccurate data duplication. It also allows a celebrity to appear in multiple seasons (e.g. the season 15 all-star season) and still allows multiple different celebrities to be in a given season, but no celebrity can be entered more than once in the same season. In the score table, the unique constraint on celebrity\_season\_id and week ensures that each celebrity's performance in a specific season can only have one score entry per week. We did this as Brupley’s original data file was set up this way (with one averaged score per week per celebrity), so that if people in the future were to enter data it ensures that the entries align with the structure of the current data and avoids inconsistencies when inserting score data. Lastly in the host\_season table, the unique constraint on season\_id and host\_id ensures that a specific host can only be assigned once per season (i.e. if Alfonso Riberio was a host for season 33 this ensures his name will not be put twice as the host in season 33). This presents duplicate rows for the same host\_id and season\_id combination and still allows a given season to have multiple unique hosts. This helps keep the data clean, reduce redundancies within this many-to-many relationship between hosts and seasons because otherwise the same host could accidentally be assigned multiple times to the same season.

Another difficulty we faced was that for Brupley’s original file included a lot of inaccurate and inconsistent data. This required deep cleaning, the addition of more data, and modifications to Brupley’s original file. Firstly, she notes that she did not include guest judges. However, when testing the creation of our judges\_score table we found that Brupley included guest judge scores making the number of judges 4 for some weeks when there should have been 3 judges. By filtering and analyzing the data, we found that this affects season 11, 12, 15, 17, 18, 21, 22, 25, 26, 28, and 32\. Therefore, our updated excel file gets rid of these errors. On top of that we also had to make sure that we did not accidentally alter seasons when there were truly 4 main judges. Through meticulous checking we found that seasons 19, 20, 23, 24, 30 and 31 were the only seasons that had 4 main judges. Also, when normalizing the scores and judges scores table we found that Brupley had inaccurately reported a couple scores as well so we had to fix this throughout the whole excel file. We found this most problematic when there were 3 or more dances performed in a week that were scored. In most of those weeks when Brupley found the average. She did not enter accurate average scores making some of the scores inconsistent (this was typically due to there being multiple nights of performances in a given week), so we fixed the scores to be rounded to 2 decimal places. We also deleted Brupley’s average score column as we found it inconsistent and incomplete. 

This project greatly improved our understanding of data manipulation, SQL script writing, and real-world database construction and allowed us to become more comfortable with using Python with SQL. This project required a lot of testing of each table along the way to ensure that there was no orphaned data or loss of data. We learned how to approach normalization thoughtfully with what we have access to and how to use views and procedures for analytical queries. This project highlighted the importance of clean, organized, normalized data and the power of relational databases in drawing insights from structured information. Overall, this project was both technically and creatively rewarding while also extremely challenging. We found it valuable to gain experience working with PostgreSQL and SQLAlchemy in Python and having this database interaction, by applying it to a topic we share an interest in.
